post_cb({"28035112": {"ViewCount": "294", "Body": "<p>How can I terminate my program (using code) <em>immediately</em>. </p>\n<ul>\n<li>I don't want destructors called.</li>\n<li>I don't want any hooks to execute.</li>\n<li>I just want the bare minimum way to kill the program.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(I'm not looking for answers that say this is not kosher. I know it's not.)</p>\n<p>EDIT: Looking for Windows and Linux solutions.</p>\n<p>EDIT2: I've tried <code>exit</code>, <code>_exit</code>, <code>abort</code>, and <code>terminate</code> without success on Windows.</p>\n<p>EDIT3: While I don't yet have access to a Linux box, I was able to successfully kill my Windows program with the following code:</p>\n<pre><code>int pid = _getpid();\nchar buff[256];\nsprintf(buff, \"taskkill /pid %d /f\", pid);\nsystem(buff);\n</code></pre>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "28035151", "Title": "How to kill my program IMMEDIATELY", "CreationDate": "2015-01-19T23:09:54.387", "Id": "28035112", "CommentCount": "2", "LastEditDate": "2015-01-20T05:05:27.473", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "239916", "LastActivityDate": "2017-11-19T22:59:55.250", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "239916", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "5"}, "28035151": {"Id": "28035151", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Just call <code>_exit()</code>, available on both <a href=\"http://linux.die.net/man/2/_exit\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Linux</a> and <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/6wdz5232.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Windows</a>. It won't produce a core-dump like <code>abort()</code> will.</p>\n<p><strong>Edit</strong>: If <code>_exit()</code> isn't good enough for you, you'll probably have to go platform-specific.</p>\n<p>On Windows, you can call <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms686714%28v=vs.85%29.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>TerminateProcess()</code></a>, which is, as far as I know, the most forceful/immediate method to kill a process exposed by the Windows API (though if there's a more forceful one I'd love to learn about it).</p>\n<p>On Linux, raising <code>SIGKILL</code> might be better, as <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28035112/how-to-kill-my-program-immediately/28035252#28035252\">suggested by Jeffery Thomas</a>. I actually don't know if <code>SIGKILL</code> is more forceful/immediate than <code>_exit()</code> or not.</p>\n<p>Both of these methods are asynchronous.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-19T23:47:06.017", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2015-01-19T23:13:49.957", "ParentId": "28035112", "CommentCount": "6", "OwnerUserId": "1287251", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T11:50:57.410"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_28035112_28035275_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 6800}}, "n3337": {"so_28035112_28035275_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 6555}}, "n4659": {"so_28035112_28035275_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 8290}}}, "28035146": {"Id": "28035146", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Use <code>_exit()</code>. This will kill your program immediatly. </p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1557304", "LastActivityDate": "2017-11-19T22:59:55.250", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2015-01-19T23:13:28.223", "ParentId": "28035112", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1557304", "LastEditDate": "2017-11-19T22:59:55.250"}, "28035275": {"Id": "28035275", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>In C++11 <code>_Exit</code> (note: uppercase <code>E</code>) is specified as \u00a718.5/3</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_28035112_28035275_0\"><strong>\u201d</strong> The program is terminated without executing destructors for objects of automatic, thread, or\n  static storage duration and without calling functions passed to <code>atexit()</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If you want possible handlers to execute then you can instead call <code>std::quick_exit</code>, which calls registered handlers and then <code>_Exit</code>.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-19T23:25:10.103", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-01-19T23:25:10.103", "ParentId": "28035112", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "464581"}, "28035252": {"Id": "28035252", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>On POSIX compliant UNIX systems, <a href=\"http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/signal.h.html\"><code>raise(SIGKILL)</code></a> will do what you want.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>For Windows, <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms686714(v=vs.85).aspx\"><code>TerminateProcess(GetCurrentProcess(),0)</code></a> is what I would look at first. NOTE: This could cause problems for globally shared DLL's.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>As a final comment, you didn't give any details, but for whatever you are trying to do, you're doing it the wrong way if this is your way out.</p>\n</hr></hr>", "LastEditorUserId": "1298400", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-19T23:42:34.497", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2015-01-19T23:22:53.287", "ParentId": "28035112", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1298400", "LastEditDate": "2015-01-19T23:42:34.497"}, "28035132": {"Id": "28035132", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Try calling the <code>abort()</code> function in C, or <code>std::terminate</code> in C++.<br>\n(<code>terminate</code> is also a C function in Visual C++, but it's nonstandard.)</br></p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "541686", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-19T23:17:37.083", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2015-01-19T23:11:58.233", "ParentId": "28035112", "CommentCount": "2", "OwnerUserId": "541686", "LastEditDate": "2015-01-19T23:17:37.083"}});